More than 58 percent of the world's coral reefs are endangered due to pollution, over-harvesting of reef fish, and other human factors, according to the World Conservation Union (IUCN).
The destruction of reefs will impact over one billion people.
Climate change and introduced species like starfish are also major threats.
Poverty and population growth contribute to the degradation of South Asia's coral reefs.
Recovery could take decades to centuries.
Artificial reefs in Taiwan aim to enhance fishery resources.
The coral reefs face threats from pollution, climate change, and overfishing, posing a significant environmental challenge.
